<figure><image xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167833328995" source="C:/Users/Wendy/ORCCA/output/images/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_10_02_302_img.jpg" width="50%"></image></figure>
</p>
</answer></exercise><p>If we look at the graphs from the previous Example and Try Its, we can identify some of the properties of exponential functions.</p>
<p>The graphs of <m>f\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m>, as well as the graphs of <m>f\left(x\right)={4}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={5}^{x}</m>, all have the same basic shape. This is the shape we expect from an exponential function where <m>b&gt;1.</m>.</p>
<p>We notice, that for each function, the graph contains the point <m>\left(0,1\right).</m> This make sense because <m>{b}^{0}=1</m> for any <m>b&gt;1</m>.</p>
<p>The graph of each function, <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x}</m> also contains the point <m>\left(1,b\right).</m> The graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(1,2\right)</m> and the graph of <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(1,3\right).</m> This makes sense as <m>{b}^{1}=b.</m></p>
<p>Notice too, the graph of each function <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x}</m> also contains the point <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{b}\right).</m> The graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{2}\right)</m> and the graph of <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{3}\right).</m> This makes sense as <m>{b}^{-1}=\frac{1}{b}.</m></p>
<p>What is the domain for each function? From the graphs we can see that the domain is the set of all real numbers. There is no restriction on the domain. We write the domain in interval notation as <m>\left(\text{âˆ’}\infty ,\infty \right).</m></p>
<p>Look at each graph. What is the range of the function? The graph never hits the <m>x</m>-axis. The range is all positive numbers. We write the range in interval notation as <m>\left(0,\infty \right).</m></p>
<p>Whenever a graph of a function approaches a line but never touches it, we call that line an <term>asymptote</term>. For the exponential functions we are looking at, the graph approaches the <m>x</m>-axis very closely but will never cross it, we call the line <m>y=0,</m> the <m>x</m>-axis, a horizontal asymptote.</p>
<note xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836699696"><title>Properties of the Graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x}</m> when <m>b&gt;1</m>
</title>
<table xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836507868">
<caption>[[CAPTION]]</caption>
<tabular><row><cell>Domain</cell><cell><m>\left(\text{âˆ’}\infty ,\infty \right)</m></cell></row><row><cell>Range</cell><cell><m>\left(0,\infty \right)</m></cell></row><row><cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell><cell>None</cell></row><row><cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell><cell><m>\left(0,1\right)</m></cell></row><row><cell>Contains</cell><cell><m>\left(1,b\right), \left(-1,\frac{1}{b}\right)</m></cell></row><row><cell>Asymptote</cell><cell><m>x</m>-axis, the line <m>y=0</m></cell></row></tabular>
</table>
<figure><image xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167829754330" source="C:/Users/Wendy/ORCCA/output/images/exp graphs 1.png" width="50%"></image></figure>
</note><p>Our definition of an exponential function <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x}</m> says <m>b&gt;0,</m> but the examples and discussion so far has been about functions where <m>b&gt;1.</m> What happens when <m>0&lt;b&lt;1</m>? The next example will explore this possibility.</p>
<example xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167833381202"><statement><p>On the same coordinate system, graph <m>f\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)}^{x}.</m></p></statement><solution xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167829688322">
