</p>
</answer></exercise><p>Now letâ€™s look at the graphs from the previous Example and Try Its so we can now identify some of the properties of exponential functions where <m>0&lt;b&lt;1.</m></p>
<p>The graphs of <m>f\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)}^{x}</m> as well as the graphs of <m>f\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)}^{x}</m> all have the same basic shape. While this is the shape we expect from an exponential function where <m>0&lt;b&lt;1,</m> the graphs go down from left to right while the previous graphs, when <m>b&gt;1,</m> went from up from left to right.</p>
<p>We notice that for each function, the graph still contains the point (0, 1). This make sense because <m>{b}^{0}=1</m> for any <m>b&gt;0</m>.</p>
<p>As before, the graph of each function, <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x},</m> also contains the point <m>\left(1,b\right).</m> The graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(1,\frac{1}{2}\right)</m> and the graph of <m>g\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(1,\frac{1}{3}\right).</m> This makes sense as <m>{b}^{1}=b.</m></p>
<p>Notice too that the graph of each function, <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x},</m> also contains the point <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{b}\right).</m> The graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(-1,2\right)</m> and the graph of <m>g\left(x\right)={\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)}^{x}</m> contained <m>\left(-1,3\right).</m> This makes sense as <m>{b}^{-1}=\frac{1}{b}</m> for any <m>b&gt;0</m>.</p>
<p>What is the domain and range for each function? From the graphs we can see that the domain is the set of all real numbers and we write the domain in interval notation as <m>\left(\text{âˆ’}\infty ,\infty \right).</m> Again, the graph never hits the <m>x</m>-axis. Thus, the range is the set of all positive numbers. We write the range in interval notation as <m>\left(0,\infty \right).</m></p>
<p>We will summarize these properties in the chart below. Which also include when <m>b&gt;1.</m></p>
<note xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836329709"><title>Properties of the Graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={a}^{x}</m>
</title>
<table xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836516046">
<caption>[[CAPTION]]</caption>
<tabular><row bottom="major"><cell>when <m>b&gt;1</m></cell><cell>when <m>0&lt;b&lt;1</m></cell></row><row><cell>Domain</cell><cell><m>\left(\text{âˆ’}\infty ,\infty \right)</m></cell><cell>Domain</cell><cell><m>\left(\text{âˆ’}\infty ,\infty \right)</m></cell></row><row><cell>Range</cell><cell><m>\left(0,\infty \right)</m></cell><cell>Range</cell><cell><m>\left(0,\infty \right)</m></cell></row><row><cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell><cell>none</cell><cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell><cell>none</cell></row><row><cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell><cell><m>\left(0,1\right)</m></cell><cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell><cell><m>\left(0,1\right)</m></cell></row><row><cell>Contains</cell><cell><m>\left(1,b\right), \left(-1,\frac{1}{b}\right)</m></cell><cell>Contains</cell><cell><m>\left(1,b\right), \left(-1,\frac{1}{b}\right)</m></cell></row><row><cell>Asymptote</cell><cell><m>x</m>-axis, the line <m>y=0</m></cell><cell>Asymptote</cell><cell><m>x</m>-axis, the line <m>y=0</m></cell></row><row><cell>Basic shape</cell><cell>increasing</cell><cell>Basic shape</cell><cell>decreasing</cell></row></tabular>
</table>
<figure><image xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836629903" source="C:/Users/Wendy/ORCCA/output/images/exp graphs 2.png" width="50%"></image></figure>
</note><p>It is important for us to notice that both of these graphs are one-to-one, as they both pass the horizontal line test. This means the exponential function will have an inverse. We will look at this later.</p>
<example xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836580200"><statement><p>On the same coordinate system graph <m>f\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}-2.</m></p></statement><solution xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836554666">
