<figure><image xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167833329115" source="C:/Users/Wendy/ORCCA/output/images/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_10_02_308_img.jpg" width="50%"></image></figure>
</p>
</answer></exercise><p>All of our exponential functions have had either an integer or a rational number as the base. We will now look at an exponential function with an irrational number as the base.</p>
<p>Before we can look at this exponential function, we need to define the irrational number, <m>e</m>. This number is used as a base in many applications in the sciences and business that are modeled by exponential functions. The number is defined as the value of <m>{\left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)}^{n}</m> as <m>n</m> gets larger and larger. We say, as <m>n</m> approaches infinity, or increases without bound. The table shows the value of <m>{\left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)}^{n}</m> for several values of <m>n</m>.</p>
<table xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836293918">
<caption>[[CAPTION]]</caption>
<tabular><row bottom="major"><cell><m>n</m></cell><cell><m>{\left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)}^{n}</m></cell></row><row><cell>1</cell><cell>2</cell></row><row><cell>2</cell><cell>2.25</cell></row><row><cell>5</cell><cell>2.48832</cell></row><row><cell>10</cell><cell>2.59374246</cell></row><row><cell>100</cell><cell>2.704813829â€¦</cell></row><row><cell>1,000</cell><cell>2.716923932â€¦</cell></row><row><cell>10,000</cell><cell>2.718145927â€¦</cell></row><row><cell>100,000</cell><cell>2.718268237â€¦</cell></row><row><cell>1,000,000</cell><cell>2.718280469â€¦</cell></row><row><cell>1,000,000,000</cell><cell>2.718281827â€¦</cell></row></tabular>
</table>
<p><men xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836731868">e\approx 2.718281827</men></p>
<p>The number <m>e</m> is like the number <m>\pi </m> in that we use a symbol to represent it because its decimal representation never stops or repeats. The irrational number <m>e</m> is called the <term>natural base</term>.</p>
<note xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167833051440">
<title>Natural Base <m>e</m>
</title>
<p>The number <m>e</m> is defined as the value of <m>{\left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)}^{n},</m> as <m>n</m> increases without bound. We say, as <m>n</m> approaches infinity,</p>
<p><men xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836540237">e\approx 2.718281827...</men></p>
</note><note xml:id="m67527-eip-680"><title>The Natural Exponential Function</title>
<p>The exponential function whose base is <m>e,</m> <m>f\left(x\right)={e}^{x}</m> is called the <term>natural exponential function</term>.
</p>
<p>Letâ€™s graph the function <m>f\left(x\right)={e}^{x}</m> on the same coordinate system as <m>g\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> and <m>h\left(x\right)={3}^{x}.</m></p></note><figure><image xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836407679" source="C:/Users/Wendy/ORCCA/output/images/CNX_IntAlg_Figure_10_02_012.jpg" width="50%"></image></figure><p>Notice that the graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={e}^{x}</m> is â€œbetweenâ€ the graphs of <m>g\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> and <m>h\left(x\right)={3}^{x}.</m> Does this make sense as <m>2&lt;e&lt;3</m>?</p></subsection><subsection xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836362502"><title>Use Exponential Models in Applications</title>
<p>Exponential functions model many situations. If you own a bank account, you have experienced the use of an exponential function. There are two formulas that are used to determine the balance in the account when interest is earned. If a principal, <m>P</m>, is invested at an interest rate, <m>r</m> (in decimal form), for <m>t</m> years, the new balance, <m>A</m>, will depend on how often the interest is compounded. If the interest is compounded <m>n</m> times a year we use the formula <m>A=P{\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)}^{nt}.</m> If the interest is compounded continuously, we use the formula <m>A=P{e}^{rt}.</m> These are the formulas for <term>compound interest</term>.</p>
<note xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836508330">
<title>Compound Interest</title>
<p>For a principal, <m>P</m>, invested at an interest rate, <m>r</m> (in decimal form), for <m>t</m> years, the new balance, <m>A</m>, is:</p>
<p><men xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167829753339">\begin{array}{}\\ \\ A=P{\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)}^{nt}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; \text{when compounded} n \text{times a year.}\hfill \\ A=P{e}^{rt}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; \text{when compounded continuously.}\hfill \end{array}</men></p>
</note><p>As you work with the interest formulas, it is often helpful to identify the values of the variables first and then substitute them into the formula.</p>
<example xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836529275"><statement><p>A total of <m>\text{$}10,000</m> was invested in a college fund for a new grandchild. If the interest rate is <m>5\text{%},</m> how much will be in the account in 18 years by each method of compounding?</p>
<p>â“ compound quarterly</p>
<p>â“‘ compound monthly</p>
<p>â“’ compound continuously</p></statement><solution xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167824737605">
<p><m>\begin{array}{cccccc}\begin{array}{c}\text{Identify the values of each variable in the formulas.}\hfill \\ \text{Remember to express the percent as a decimal.}\hfill \end{array}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; \begin{array}{ccc}\hfill A&amp; =\hfill &amp; ?\hfill \\ \hfill P&amp; =\hfill &amp; \text{$}10,000\hfill \\ \hfill r&amp; =\hfill &amp; 0.05\hfill \\ \hfill t&amp; =\hfill &amp; 18 \text{years}\hfill \end{array}\hfill \end{array}</m></p>
<p>â“
<m>\begin{array}{cccccc}\begin{array}{c}\text{For quarterly compounding,} n=4. \text{There are 4}\hfill \\ \text{quarters in a year.}\hfill \end{array}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=P{\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)}^{nt}\hfill \\ \text{Substitute the values in the formula.}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=10,000{\left(1+\frac{0.05}{4}\right)}^{4Â·18}\hfill \\ \begin{array}{c}\text{Compute the amount. Be careful to consider the}\hfill \\ \text{order of operations as you enter the expression into}\hfill \\ \text{your calculator.}\hfill \end{array}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=\text{$}24,459.20\hfill \end{array}</m></p>
<p>â“‘
<m>\begin{array}{cccccc}\begin{array}{c}\text{For monthly compounding,} n=12. \text{There are 12}\hfill \\ \text{months in a year.}\hfill \end{array}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=P{\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)}^{nt}\hfill \\ \text{Substitute the values in the formula.}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=10,000{\left(1+\frac{0.05}{12}\right)}^{12Â·18}\hfill \\ \text{Compute the amount.}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=\text{$}24,550.08\hfill \end{array}</m></p>
<p>â“’
<m>\begin{array}{cccccc}\text{For compounding continuously,}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=P{e}^{rt}\hfill \\ \text{Substitute the values in the formula.}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=10,000{e}^{0.05Â·18}\hfill \\ \text{Compute the amount.}\hfill &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp; &amp;  A=\text{$}24,596.03\hfill \end{array}</m></p>
</solution></example><exercise xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836326753"><statement xml:id="m67527-fs-id1167836527053">
<p>Angela invested <m>\text{$}15,000</m> in a savings account. If the interest rate is <m>4\text{%},</m> how much will be in the account in 10 years by each method of compounding?</p>
